Let's now calculate the value of our deposit for 20 years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$4,500\times\dfrac{\left(1+.097\right)^{20}-1}{.097}
\\[10pt]
&=\$4,500\times\dfrac{5.369899076}{.097}
\\[10pt]
&=\$4,500\times55.35978429
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$249,119.03}
\end{aligned}$$

**Therefore, the value of the deposits after 20 years is $249,119.03**

Next, let's determine the value of the deposits if the period is 40 years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$4,500\times\dfrac{\left(1+.097\right)^{40}-1}{.097}
\\[10pt]
&=\$4,500\times\dfrac{39.57561424}{.097}
\\[10pt]
&=\$4,500\times407.9960231
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$1,835,982.10}
\end{aligned}$$


**Therefore, if we deposit $4,500 for the next 40 years, the future value is $1,835,982.10.**
